 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uarlis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arlis</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 4:08:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> I agree with Scirocco and Tudamorf with regards to the definitions as they have been defined in this thread. The problem (as I see it anyway) is that the term PvP which you initially used has too many preconceived and bad connotations to many people.<br>
<br>
For the majority of people when you used the term PvP it is equated in their minds (or it seems so to me) with a PKer. The two things in a roleplaying aspect are quite different, but appear to be equated for most people.<br>
<br>
This gives you a huge uphill battle in the point you are trying to make. Not only are you trying to demonstrate your point, but you also have to get your target audience to change the perceptions that they have with regards to certain terms.<br>
<br>
As a lawyer Scirocco you know quite well the kind of effect that what words you actually use can have on your target audience. You have said it before Scirocco, how you say something to your target audience is as important or more important that the message itself.<br>
<br>
In this case I'd say that using PvP was a poor choice of terminology. I realize that you have later attempted to change that, but still, the impression has been made in the original post.<br>
<br>
All that being said (I'm a wordy child born out of wedlock sometimes...), I agree with you. Having a human on the other side of an encounter is more interesting than facing off against a set AI encounter.<br>
<br>
I have been a DM/GM for over 20 years. A GM (or at least in my opinion) has to vary the stance that he takes throughout a game session. Going from being 'The Friend' to 'The Opportunist' to 'The Enemy'.<br>
<br>
A good encounter should be unpredicatable in nature. It should be more in the nature of, 'Is this character working for us or against us in this situation? Even if he is now... can we depend on him if the situation should change?' The fact that an NPC_Mercenary_01 has worked for you in the past shouldn't leave a group with the feeling that... 'Oh, he's here to help us with this encounter because we hired him out 3 weeks ago. Or he'll help us because he is a guard.' Is the mob/npc honest, dishonest, altering his behavior because his superiors are around, not around, etc.<br>
<br>
Having a mob/NPC that blindly charges the group and then flees when at 15% health doesn't do much to get the blood going for most folks. Having an encounter where the big bad guy takes a hit and runs off to grab underlings to send into the fray first to weaken you and then comes at you, tends to make for a more interesting encounter for most folks.<br>
<br>
And for what it's worth. D&amp;D came from the game Chainmail which was a wargame where sides could have hundreds of troops on a side. The different groups of troops tended to be led by heroes of surpassing skill. It was definately PvP. <p>Arlis
