<br>
Not really.  Just trying to help them pierce through all the baggage attached to the term &quot;PvP&quot; to see what truly underlies it.  And why people find it objectionable.   Which is HvH.   Which is also the core of P&amp;P RPGs, where it is usually not objectionable.<br>
<br>
And then, after making the realization that HvH doesn't have to be bad (and, in fact, is often essential to a good story or game), coming back to think anew about how HvH can be incorporated into MMORPGs in a good way.<br>
<br>
If you have a strong adverse reaction to &quot;PvP&quot; in MMORPGs, ask yourself why.  And why don't you have the same reaction to PvE?<br>
<br>
Assume that the consequences are the same.  Both can kill you.  Both can cause XP loss (or not).  Both can cause equipment loss (or not).  Would that change your answer, or would you still find PvP objectionable?  <br>
<br>
If so, then the only difference at that point is the human behind your adversary.  HvH.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umeddik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meddik</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://aodoctors.homestead.com/files/cross.jpg BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 10:04:36 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> <B>If you have a strong adverse reaction to "PvP" in MMORPGs, ask yourself why. And why don't you have the same reaction to PvE?</B><br>
<br>
The basic problem is that as the size of any community increases linearly, the apparent number of grief players increases exponentially.<br>
<br>
I am MUCH more likely to run into exploiters, griefers, jerks, and people just out for the experience of ruining my playtime as the size of a community grows.<br>
<br>
In a Pen and paper campaign, it is Very very rare that you find someone whose main goal is to ruin the fun for others. But as a community gets larger, it happens more and more.<br>
<br>
Plus, on a MMORPG, the rules (or code) ends up getting incredibly complex. There will be exploitable bugs, loopholes, and unintended weaknesses that other players will use to ruin the game play of others.<br>
<br>
I know, that PvP is not the only way that someone else can affect me in a game. However, it is commonly one of the first methods any grief player will take, assuming that it is available. Why? Because its the simplest route to ruin someone else's gameplay. <p><center><B>Meddik,</B> Rebel Doctor
