 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=badaf>Badaf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 2:30:16 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Um</span><hr size=1> Scirocco<br>
&gt;&gt;How can i, as a D&amp;D DM, have created enjoyable adventures where there was no player vs DM-controlled characters? <br>
<br>
&quot;Simple. You didn't.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're fooling yourself if you don't think that there were DM-controlled characters in your games. I'm assuming you had the usual run of NPCs and monsters for the PCs to fight.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So tell me, what did the players fight, if not NPCs or monsters?&quot;<br>
<br>
They didnt fight. While im a bit insulted by your narrow-mindedness by saying i didn't do something that i did, i will provide examples where combat didnt take place.  <br>
<br>
Module 1. <br>
<br>
Players were placed in a highly political situation. Combat was not an option. They had to use political influence, land bargaining, trade concessions, and negotiation skills to quell a potential war. <br>
<br>
Module 2. <br>
<br>
Players went through a dungeon with NO creatures at all. Only puzzle-solving and trap avoidance were needed to succeed. <br>
<br>
Module 3. <br>
<br>
Attacking any creature in this module would result in triple exp lose equivalent to what exps they would have gained killing it. All creatures were under protection of a deity who controlled this realm. While, technically, this could have involved some combat, the players managed to complete the module without a single confrontation. <br>
<br>
Module 4. <br>
<br>
Players were given a mission to infiltrate a heavily guarded castle and steal a critical quest item. Due to the ability of the castle's clerics and mages, any combat would eventually lead to their capture and had to be avoided at all cost in order to succeed. <br>
<br>
Module 5. <br>
<br>
Players found themselves imprisoned deep in enemy territory. The enemies were very powerful and could easily destroy the party. Players had to escape undetected. <br>
<br>
All these examples are modules i created. Me and the players involved had a very enjoyable time in each one of them. So please do not insult me by telling me i didn't do it. <br>
<br>
&quot;Unfortunately, I think that MMORPGs do this already. You can't really call EQ a true RPG, can you? Even the proposed &quot;RPing&quot; server won't do the job....&quot;<br>
<br>
Depends on how you take it. Me and my guild RP 100% of the time in EQ. If its not a &quot;true&quot; RPG then i dont know what is. I will say the environment in EQ is not very conducive to roleplaying. The only reward we get for roleplaying is self-satisfaction and acknowledgement from ourselves and other RPers. But that doesn't stop us. We have never been one to back down from a challenge. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubroomhilda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Broomhilda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/11/01 4:10:45 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .....</span><hr size=1> Actually Badaf, the 'modules' you just came up with are very similar to a game series like 'Thief' where stealth was the recommended course of action, although fighting was a part of it.  In anycase, the majority of people dont want to stealth through things without some sort of confrontations, and after repetetion it would get boring and linear if it was all stealth or non-confrontational.  I'm trying to stay away from generalizing as much as possible, but i also want to be as realistic as possible.  Imo, most people dont prefer to do just trade skills, dancing in AO, or other things some roleplayers consider enjoyable.  There really is no excitement or thrill in that because there is no danger.  Danger is what makes somebody sit at the edge of their seat with their adrenaline pumping.  I dont think i'll ever have my adrenaline pump in EQ again, because i've become so used to the typical actions of the AI.  <br>
<br>
Of course not everybody plays games for the same reasons and this difference in play styles is why people need to be separated.  Also the envy/jealousy factor, because most games are based on fighting to advance or to survive.  Roleplayers that would rather do skills end up being beat up on(as in UO), or arent able to advance as fast(as in EQ) without confrontations.  They end up having a problem with the way the game mechanics allow others that choose to fight to become stronger faster than they do.  So they wait and wait in hopes for a MMORPG to come out that caters to the non-confrontational play style or at least puts that on an even keel with those that choose to fight.   I can remember some people posting about the ability AO was going to have to allow them to lvl without having to fight.  And AO has this feature, but a person choosing this method of play will never have the equality they want with those that choose to fight.  Imo fighitng is the basis of games, or at least mass marketed games.  A game that catered to the non-confrontational play-style would be catering to a very specialized and smaller audience.  Not to be demeaning but a game without confrontation is not much of a game imo.    <br>
<br>
I dont think D&amp;D was true PvP, since the DM often wasnt trying to beat the players, but rather make it challenging and an enjoyable experience.  People dont like to die or lose anything they own, which is another problem that PvP games have to account for, as well as the DM in regards to D&amp;D(So the DM is forced to 'dummy' himself abit).  There will always be players that arent better, or more powerful than others, and will end up being victimized in PvP.  Many times these players dont want to adapt and want the system changed to protect them, and thats what usually occurs.  There is NEVER an even playing field in PvP MMORPG's mostly due to connection and computer.  Then you have the resources available for one player that might not be there for another, or the skill in combat of one player(who is very into PvP) as opposed to the casual PvP.  So some people will always make excuses and always want change to protect and cater to them.  This will never change.<br>
<br>
The bottom line here is that i agree that IF a MMORPG were able to incorporate a free PvP environment with little to no AI or artificial mechanics, but the free will of players to enact justice and keep the world relatively chaos free, then that would be the pinnacle a MMORPG can reach.  Storylines and community would happen naturally, in the same way when you put 6 people together in a house(as in the REAL WORLD), and then it gets interesting, then televised ).  Communities battling other communities over ideals or some soap opera'sh falling out is what gets people 'into' the game.  Would you rather read a book or experience the book?  Would you rather somebody make up a fictional storyline or a storyline that naturally formed on its own?  But like i said, some people would rather 'read' the book, or prefer the madeup 'fictional' storyline, just like some people prefer AI for a gaming experience.  <br>
<br>
Btw, i wanted to stay away from the premise of the argument about 'RPG', since it seems to be defined differently for many people.  And i dont believe D&amp;D was the pinnacle a game can reach, nor do i believe trying to reach the extreme definition of what 'RPG' stands for equates to 'fun'.  Imo, the bottom line of a game is fun.  Actually, i think a pure 'RPG' game(or a hardcore roleplayers idea of a game) would be quite boring to alot of people.  In AO, there is a 'bug' with NPC vendors that only allows only one person to be able to see the menu and buy at a time, so a line is formed(of which people dont honor and leads to all kinds of arguments and name calling but thats beside the point).  There are roleplayers that prefer this because they believe its realistic and more conduscive to roleplaying.  Imagine that, from my perspective its just a big hassle and downtime.  From a roleplayers perspective it allows them to emote me and show off their roleplay skills.  /shrug<br>
<br>
Splitting up the play styles is the best chance a game has to making everybody happy.  I dont want a game based on roleplaying, i want a game thats fun.  My favorite games are the ones that allow for player development and customization(roleplaying elements) as well as excitement and danger(PvP).  Obviously some feel differently.  How are we supposed to both be happy within the same game structure?  Especially in a free PvP environment?  Keep in mind the expectations of equality.... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=badaf>Badaf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/12/01 6:45:04 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .....</span><hr size=1> Broomhilda:<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually Badaf, the 'modules' you just came up with are very similar to a game series like 'Thief' where stealth was the recommended course of action, although fighting was a part of it. In anycase, the majority of people dont want to stealth through things without some sort of confrontations, and after repetetion it would get boring and linear if it was all stealth or non-confrontational.&quot;<br>
