 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/12/01 12:03:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tangent, please ignore</span><hr size=1> Let's get one thing straight at the start.  HvH does NOT require physical combat.  Human conflict takes many forms.  <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Module 1. Players were placed in a highly political situation. Combat was not an option. They had to use political influence, land bargaining, trade concessions, and negotiation skills to quell a potential war. <br>
<br>
And who did they use that political influence on, who did they bargain with, who did they negotiate with?  If with you playing the role of the other side through NPCs, then it was HvH.  If the players were taking opposing sides amongst themselves, it was even more obviously HvH. <br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Module 2. Players went through a dungeon with NO creatures at all. Only puzzle-solving and trap avoidance were needed to succeed. <br>
<br>
See previous posts for comments on GMs or DMs taking an adversarial role through the environment.  As I said above, PvE in a P&amp;P RPG is usually still HvH.  <br>
<br>
You as the GM needed to be there to determine if the puzzle was solved or the traps sprung or avoided, right?  If you were absent, could the players still have done the module?<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Module 3. Attacking any creature in this module would result in triple exp lose equivalent to what exps they would have gained killing it. All creatures were under protection of a deity who controlled this realm. While, technically, this could have involved some combat, the players managed to complete the module without a single confrontation. <br>
<br>
Who controlled the creatures they were avoiding?  You did, I assume.  HvH.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; Module 4.  Players were given a mission to infiltrate a heavily guarded castle and steal a critical quest item. Due to the ability of the castle's clerics and mages, any combat would eventually lead to their capture and had to be avoided at all cost in order to succeed. <br>
<br>
Who controlled the clerics and mages they were avoiding?  You did, I assume.  And who would have controlled those clerics and mages if combat was not avoided?  You did, I assume.  HvH.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; Module 5. Players found themselves imprisoned deep in enemy territory. The enemies were very powerful and could easily destroy the party. Players had to escape undetected. <br>
<br>
Who controlled the enemies they were avoiding?  You did, I assume.  HvH.<br>
<br>
I suspected that you might come back with some examples like these.  That's why I said you were fooling yourself.  It wasn't meant as a personal insult.<br>
